{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Human Memory\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Memory is one of the most important features for interacting with software. We don't want software to provide a high load for human memory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The human memory has three distinct stages. Information is:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Received through one or more of the {\i sensory memories}, e.g.:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Iconic (visual) memory\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Echoic (auditory) memory\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Haptic memory\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab These memories are very detailed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab They are specific to the medium they are storing, unlike short-term memory, which is more abstract and independent of the senses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Kind of raw sensation.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Selectively held in {\i short-term memory} while it is analysed, after which it may be either discarded or:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab This is independent of the senses and more abstract than sensory memories\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Stored permanently in {\i long-term memory}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab We store a description (maybe a very rich description) of the sensory memories.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 How can we use this transit to our advantage?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Sensory Memories\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These store raw memories (images, sounds, etc.) for very short periods of time (typically just a few seconds).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can store things for longer if we get no new stimuli/sensations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 E.g. if we have no new visual stimuli, we can hold raw memory of a visual stimulus for longer.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 He'll talk later about how we know how these work.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Short-term Memory\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Short-term memory involves largely conscious recall of information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Information held in the sensory memories may be passed to the short-term memory for analysis and processing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the capacity of STM is limited and hence only some sensory information receives attention.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Information held in short-term memory can be accessed in around 70ms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The short-term memory can hold around seven items of information ("seven plus or minus two" \u8211- Miller, 1956). However, is it not easy to define an item of information. It might be:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A single digit or character or word\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A long number or entire phrase, if that number or phrase is already known to the person\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, if you hear an unfamiliar place-name, you may initially store it as a sequence of syllables. Once you become familiar with the name, it can be stored as a single item in short-term memory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When hearing a series of numbers, some people stored 7 separate numbers, and some people stored patterns in the numbers, e.g. "my telephone number".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Storing information in short-term memory involves mental effort.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Because of this, information held in STM is easily lost:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab an interruption may demand our attention, forcing other information out of STM\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab it's difficult to maintain information in STM for more than very short periods, so a long delay may result in items being lost\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab information is discarded when it no longer appears useful, so e.g. completing a task may cause us to flush all associated information from STM\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Example: ATM\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Early ATMs varied in the order in which they performed these tasks. Most returned the card last of all, when all requested services had been completed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Users left after collecting their money or balance statement. They forgot to collect their card, because collecting the money was the primary task.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Collecting the card was a secondary task. On completion of a primary task, secondary tasks are often forgotten.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Most modern ATMs return the card before carrying out the requested services. This was it's harder to leave the card behind.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Summary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Short-term memory is the gateway to long-term memory. Information is held in STM while is it being learned.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We don't take anything into our long-term memory without conscious thought.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Long-term Memory\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Long-term memory provides permanent storage of information. Information held in long-term memory can be accessed in around 100 ms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The capacity of long-term memory is huge, apparently unlimited. Forgetting takes place slowly, if at all.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Recall after a few hours or days is usually no different from recall after a few minutes. Decay stabilises vs. short-term memory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If information makes it to long-term memory, it is effortless to store it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are three main processes associated with long-term memory:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Storage/learning\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Information retrieval\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Forgetting\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Also how we confuse things\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Storage/learning\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Information passes into long-term memory via the short-term memory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Not everything that is held in short-term memory is eventually stored in long-term memory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The main factors determining what is stored are:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Rehearsal\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab If you rehearse something enough, you can transfer almost anything into memory\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Meaning\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab If something is meaningful to you, you will store it much more quickly\sa180\sa180\par}
