{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Long-term Memory (continued)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Storage/Learning\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Rehearsal (repeated exposure to data or consideration of it) increases the likelihood that it will be stored in LTM.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Ebbinghaus found that the likelihood of long-term recall is directly proportional to the total period of exposure to the material \u8211- the total time hypothesis.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Baddeley found that the likelihood of long-term recall varied according to the pattern of exposure rather than the total period.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Brief but regular exposure produced long-term recall more effectively than infrequent, prolonged exposure \u8211- the distribution of practice effect.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Though it might be to do with re-ordering of info by the brain when you sleep.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Meaningful information is more likely to be stored in LTM than meaningless data.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Bartlett found that subjects who were asked to learn a story about an unfamiliar culture tended to recast the story within their own culture, and this aided recall.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab He coined the phrase effort after meaning to describe the way in which people organise information to make it easier to recall.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Learning may be improved by reinforcement through several senses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Baddeley notes that performing any kind of action while reading or listening to material increases the likelihood that it will be recalled.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Using key-clicks to cycles through a list promotes learning more than merely pressing once to access the entire list.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab The key-clicks help create a richer memory trace\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Research has also shown that reading material and hearing it spoken at the same time improves recall.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab It doesn't seem to make much difference whether the spoken version is produced by another voice or by the reader's own voice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab This may be why people often read aloud when trying to memorise something: reading aloud or even mouthing the words silently (sub-vocalisation) - improves recall.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Information Retrieval\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two types of information retrieval from LTM:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Recall: The recovery of information as a result of a conscious search\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Recognition: The automatic recovery of information as a result of an external stimulus.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Recognition is the less complex cognitive activity, and is almost instant.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For this reason, modern computer interfaces rely heavily on recognition rather than recall.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Instead of having to recall commands - as in a command-line system - users merely have to recognise commands from menus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Recall\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 During recall, we access long-term memory either episodically or semantically.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Episodic memory represent our memory of events and experiences.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab It allows us to access items in serial form, reconstructing sequences of events and experiences from earlier points in our lives.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Semantic memory represents relationships between information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab It allows us to access information without regard to the order in which it was acquired or the sense through which it was acquired.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Semantic memory is assumed to be arranged as a semantic network.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Items are arranged in classes, and may inherit attributes from parent classes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Researchers have shown that the delays which occur in recall can be modelled accurately as a network. The greater the number of levels in the hierarchy that have to be traversed, the longer the recall.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We don't know that this is the way it works, but it fits the facts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Recognition jumps straight into the network instead of having to traverse it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Forgetting\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two main theories to explain the loss of information from long-term memory: decay and interference.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab decay: Ebbinghaus concluded that information is lost through natural decay.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab His experiments suggested that the decay is exponential, i.e. information is lost rapidly at first but then more slowly.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Interference: new information may replace or corrupt older information\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab For example, changing your telephone number may cause you to forget your old number\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This is known as retroactive interference\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab However, there may also be times when older information 'resurfaces' and becomes confused with newer information\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For example, you may suddenly recall an old telephone number and confuse it with your new one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This is known as proactive inhibition.\sa180\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many psychologists believe that we never really forget anything - we just lose access to certain parts of the stored information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is almost impossible to prove, since losing access to data has the same effect as losing the data.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, phenomena such as proactive inhibition suggest that information remains stored even when it appears to have been lost.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Memory Use and Computer Interaction\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When using a computer, human memory is used to store various types of information:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Long-term memory:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab System commands, features, etc.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Short-term memory:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab {\i status variables} such as position within task sequence, current mode, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab {\i task variables} such as factors affecting your choices, selections previously made, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab {\i new system knowledge/skills} such as commands, features, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab {\i new non-system knowledge/skills} such as e-learning content\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Long-term Memory\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Generally not seen as that big an issue compared to short-term memory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The main concern in relation to LTM is supporting recognition rather than recall. Some techniques are:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Choose meaningful icons, command/function names\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use appropriate screen layout, grouping of icons, menu structure, etc. so that icons and menu items are easy to find\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Short-term Memory\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The main concerns in relation to short-term memory are:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab minimising the load presented at any one time\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab minimising the period for which items have to be remembered\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Various techniques can be used to minimise the problems posed by status variables, task variables, and the learning of new knowledge/skills.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Status Variables\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab identify options which have been selected of rejected (e.g. by providing a summary)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab identify visited links (by changing their colour)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab minimise the use of modes and/or provide visual reminders (e.g. changing cursor shape or screen layout)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab users may forget what they're waiting for if a response is too slow or a sequence is too complex, so provide:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab summaries of requested data, search terms, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab maps/overviews of search paths\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab visual reminders of status, e.g. breadcrumb trails\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Task Variables\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Place relevant information on one screen (use screen as external memory)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab e.g. allow side-by-side comparison of products\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li1080 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab moving backwards and forwards between pages to compare products is very demanding on memory\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab use a consistent data format to simplify consideration/comparison\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab highlight similarities/differences\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Allow users to make selections/vary parameters/etc. and see the results continuously rather than discretely\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab e.g. use a slider to set maximum price, update display as slider is moved\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab This could be described as using sensory memory (specifically visual memory) rather than short-term memory\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Material to Be Learned\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make terms meaningful\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Use a consistent naming convention, consistent syntax\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Place them within a relevant structure (e.g. spatial layout)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Allow users to explore material through multiple modalities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab e.g. sight, hearing, touch\sa180\sa180\par}
